(Introduction to Cell Biology) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The Cell) Tj
T*
(The cell is the basic structural and functional unit of all living organisms.) Tj
T*
(Cells are broadly classified into two types: prokaryotic and eukaryotic.) Tj
T*
(Prokaryotic cells, such as bacteria, lack a membrane-bound nucleus.) Tj
T*
(Eukaryotic cells, found in plants and animals, contain a true nucleus and) Tj
T*
(membrane-bound organelles such as mitochondria and the endoplasmic reticulum.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The Cell Membrane) Tj
T*
(The cell membrane is a phospholipid bilayer that surrounds the cell.) Tj
T*
(It is selectively permeable, controlling the movement of substances in and out.) Tj
T*
(Transport across the membrane occurs by diffusion, osmosis, and active transport.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Photosynthesis) Tj
T*
(Photosynthesis is the process by which green plants convert light energy into) Tj
T*
(chemical energy stored in glucose. It occurs in the chloroplasts.) Tj
T*
(The overall equation is: 6CO2 + 6H2O + light energy -> C6H12O6 + 6O2.) Tj
T*
(Photosynthesis has two stages: the light-dependent reactions and the Calvin cycle.) Tj
T*
(The light reactions occur in the thylakoid membranes and produce ATP and NADPH.) Tj
T*
(The Calvin cycle occurs in the stroma and fixes carbon dioxide into sugar.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Cellular Respiration) Tj
T*
(Cellular respiration releases energy from glucose to produce ATP.) Tj
T*
(It consists of glycolysis, the Krebs cycle, and the electron transport chain.) Tj
T*
(Aerobic respiration requires oxygen and yields about 36 ATP per glucose molecule.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(DNA and Genetics) Tj
T*
(DNA \(deoxyribonucleic acid\) carries the genetic instructions for life.) Tj
T*
(It is composed of nucleotides containing adenine, thymine, guanine, and cytosine.) Tj
T*
(Adenine pairs with thymine, and guanine pairs with cytosine.) Tj
T*
(Genes are segments of DNA that code for specific proteins.) Tj
T*
(During cell division, DNA is replicated so each daughter cell receives a copy.) Tj
T*
(Mitosis produces two identical diploid cells, while meiosis produces four) Tj
T*
(genetically distinct haploid gametes used in sexual reproduction.) Tj
T*
